    {
      "step_id": "c3d004be",
      "step_index": 9,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### 5) VERIFY / check for contradictions and uncertainties\n- **Could high polarity from the salt reduce inhibition?** The malate counterions increase apparent polarity/solubility, but CYP binding depends on the **free base** at the enzyme site. The core still contains a **lipophilic polyaromatic system** and a **strong cationic center**, so inhibition remains likely.\n- **Could excessive ionization reduce membrane access to CYP?** Highly cationic compounds can have reduced passive permeability, but many strong CYP2D6 inhibitors are cationic and still reach hepatic CYPs (often via distribution/transport and high liver exposure).\n- **Any reason it might be a substrate rather than inhibitor?** It could be both; many CYP2D6 inhibitors are also substrates. But the **bulky tricyclic scaffold + strong binding cationic center** favors inhibition.",
